JOHANNESBURG - Cash-strapped Mango Airlines on Wednesday confirmed that it plans to pay out the full salaries for the months of July, August and September to its employees. The embattled airline met with creditors and employee representatives on Wednesday, in the hope of finding a way forward for the carrier's business rescue efforts. Last week, the low-cost airline was placed in voluntary business rescue due to financial and operational problems. READ: 'I don't have anything' - Mango employees tell of struggles to make ends meet A major issue has been the non-payment of staff who are owed R157 million in unpaid salaries. Mango Airlines said the payment of salaries to its more than 750 employees would depend on money being released by the public enterprises department and its parent company the South African Airways, however, it believes salaries for July will be paid out soon. Earlier this week, Eyewitness News revealed how Mango staff members had been surviving with no income for months, with some running into trouble with the banks while others had lost all their assets and life policies. ALSO READ: Mango to host first creditors meeting with business rescue practitioner Mangoâ€™s Benediction Zubane said they were confident that the airline would be operational. The employee committee will meet again on Friday, while the airline is urging customers to contact them about tickets, vouchers, and other matters. Download the Eyewitness News app to your iOS  or Android device.